## Migration: `TimedExecutor` â†’ .NET 8

### Pattern Classification

Your code matches **Timeout enforcement** â€” aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit. It also uses `ThreadAbortException` + `ResetAbort` as control flow. All three APIs (`Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`) throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) in .NET 6+.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if work() itself never checks the token.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls to Watch For

| Pitfall | What happens | Mitigation |
|---------|-------------|------------|
| **Work doesn't stop on cancel** | `Task.WaitAsync` stops *waiting*, but `work()` keeps running on the thread pool in the background. Unlike `Thread.Abort`, nothing forcibly kills it. | If `work` is your code, accept a `CancellationToken` and check it: `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()`. See overload below. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | You can't inject cancellation into code you don't control. | Move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout â€” the only true equivalent to `Thread.Abort`. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` uses an internal timer; not disposing it leaks resources. | Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Could swallow a cancellation from a *parent* token, not just your timeout. | Use the `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter shown above. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort` equivalent** | There is none â€” cooperative cancellation doesn't need it. The thread was never interrupted in the first place. | Simply remove it. |

### Preferred Overload (cooperative cancellation)

If you control `work`, add a `CancellationToken`-aware overload so work **actually stops**:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        return Task.Run(() => work(token), token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then cooperate:

```csharp
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return items.Count;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### What Changed and Why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---------------|--------|--------|
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` | Uses the thread pool; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.WaitAsync(token)` | Cancellable wait (.NET 6+ API) |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (implicit via timer) | Cooperative cancellation â€” the only model supported |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No forced abort means nothing to reset |
